Here is a C++ program that uses recursion to find the nth Fibonacci number:

```c++
#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

int fibonacci(int n) {
   if(n == 0){
      return 0;
   } else if(n == 1)
   {
      return 1;
   } else {
      return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2);
   }
}

int main() {
   int n;
   cout << "Enter the number of terms:";
   cin >> n;
   cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is " << fibonacci(n);
   return 0;
}
```

This program works by defining the base case for the Fibonacci sequence (the first two terms are 0 and 1), and then recursively calling the `fibonacci()` function for the n-1th term and the n-2th term until it reaches the base case.

Please note that this method is not efficient for large numbers due to the large amount of repeated calculations. A more efficient approach would be to use dynamic programming or memoization to store the results of previous calculations.

